He called on residents to report a case of any parent who may be missing a child.
"The baby is under the custody of the government and we have launched investigations into why she was dumped at the specific place," Okiring said.
He said they have already collected statements from several people and they will soon narrow down on the suspect.
Witnesses told the Nation that the baby was wrapped in warm clothes and left sleeping on the floor.





Mrs Margret Akinyi, a trader, said the baby might have woken up hungry, prompting the incessant wails that alerted passersby.
Traders named the child Esther Nichiole before she was taken to Kamagambo Police Station and later transferred Rongo Children Department.
